Kuznetsova, 2010, published in Bioorganicheskaya Khimiya, 2010, Vol. 36, No. 5, pp. 607–621. Recent years have witnessed considerable progress in the investigation of marine microorganisms. Never(cid:2) theless, little is known about sea bacteria in the context of  the  production  of  new  bioactive  substances.  The preparation  of  novel  structural  types  of  biologically active compounds and the detection of highly efficient producers  of  such  compounds  are  the  main  factors that  attract  scientists’  attention  to  marine  microbial metabolites.  Marine  actinobacteria  are  a  promising source of bioactive compounds [1–6]. These bacteria live in sea water in the form of a few colonies, most of which  cannot  grow  under  lab  conditions.  They  are constantly present in bottom sediments, but they sel(cid:2) dom  constitute  more  than  10%  of  the  living  microf(cid:2) lora. Most actinobacterium representatives can be iso(cid:2) lated from beaches, coastal water, bottom sediments, and fish skin [7, 8]. The taxonomy of nearly half of the marine  actinobacterium  collection  cannot  be  deter(cid:2) mined  to  the  genus  level,  thereby  confirming  the uniqueness of oceanic populations [9]. Some  authors  believe  that  marine  actinobacteria come to the sea from land and remain as metabolically inactive spores [10]. Therefore, the study of secondary metabolites  isolated  from  the  sea  often  reveals  com(cid:2) pounds already described as metabolites of terrestrial

1 Corresponding  author;  phone/fax:  (4232)  31(cid:2)40(cid:2)50;  e(cid:2)mail: Abstract—Data on the chemical structures and biologic activities of metabolites of obligate and facultative marine actinobacteria published between 2000 and 2007 are reviewed. The structural features of five groups of metabolites related to macrolides and compounds containing lactone, quinone, and diketopiperazine res(cid:2) idues; cyclic peptides; alkaloids; and compounds of combined nature are discussed. The review shows the large chemical diversity of metabolites of actinobacteria isolated from marine ecotopes. In addition to metabolites identical  to  those  previously  isolated  from  terrestrial  actinobacteria,  marine  actinobacteria  produce  com(cid:2) pounds  not  found  in  other  natural  sources,  including  microorganisms.  Probably,  the  biosynthesis  of  new chemotypes of bioactive compounds by marine actinobacteria is related to the chemical adaptation of micro(cid:2) organisms to the marine environment. The review emphasizes the importance of chemical studies of metabo(cid:2) lites produced by marine actinobacteria. These studies will provide new data on marine microbial producers of  biologically  active  compounds  and  the  chemical  structures  and  biologic  activities  of  new  natural  low(cid:2) molecular(cid:2)weight bioregulators. Key words: marine actinobacteria, Streptomyces sp.,  Salinospora sp., Marinophilus sp., Micromonospora sp., Actinomadura sp., biologically active compounds DOI: 10.1134/S1068162010050031 Biologically Active Metabolites of Marine Actinobacteria M. actinobacteria [11]. Nevertheless, it has been reported that  marine  actinobacteria  often  produce  new  struc(cid:2) tural types of metabolites [12, 13]. The interest in the ecological role of actinobacteria in  the  marine  environment,  their  diversity,  distribu(cid:2) tion, growth conditions, and adaptation to life in the sea is quickened by the detection of marine actinobac(cid:2) terium  taxa.  These  facets  of  marine  actinobacterium biology are important for the assessment of the poten(cid:2) tial of these organisms as producers of novel secondary metabolites. As reported by Jensen [1], only two gen(cid:2) era of genuine marine actinobacteria have been found: Salinospora and Marinophilus. Bacteria of these genera produce compounds that can be considered chemical markers. For example, unusual bicyclic γ lactams, sali(cid:2) nosporamides  A  (I)  and  B  (II),  have  been  isolated from Salinospora. Compound (I) is a potent inhibitor of the proteolytic activity of the mammalian 20S pro(cid:2) teasome: IC50 = 1.3 nM. At present, it is undergoing a clinical trial as an antitumor drug at the San Diego bio(cid:2) technological  company,  United  States.  Salinospora(cid:2) mide B (II) differs from (I) in that it lacks chlorine. Its activity is less than that of (I) by a factor of 500. Salinosporamides  are  analogs  of  omuralide  [14] isolated from terrestrial sources. However, the methyl group of the latter is replaced in (I) by chloroethyl, and (I) is 35 times more active as an inhibitor of mamma(cid:2) lian proteasomes [1]. It is likely that the presence of chlorine in secondary metabolites favors their adapta(cid:2) tion to sea conditions, as chlorine is abundant in sea

water.  Chlorinated  analogs  are  typically  more  active. The isolation of a series of salinosporamides from Sali(cid:2) nospora tropica was reported in 2007 [15]. Another chemotype was found in the actinobacteria of the genus Marinophilus. They produce polyene mac(cid:2) rolides: marinomycins A (III) and B (IV). These com(cid:2) Thus,  the  ability  of  actinobacteria  of  the  genera Salinospora and Marinophilus to produce new second(cid:2) ary metabolites may be related to their adaptation to sea  conditions.  However,  this  hypothesis  should  be tested by more examples. We can say that the strategy of the search for new genuinely marine actinobacte(cid:2) rium taxa determines the strategy of the search for new secondary metabolite chemotypes. This  review  covers  bioactive  compounds  of  some types  isolated  from  actinobacteria  between  2000  and 2007. RUSSIAN  JOURNAL  OF  BIOORGANIC  CHEMISTRY   Vol.  36  BIOLOGICALLY  ACTIVE  METABOLITES  OF  MARINE  ACTINOBACTERIA Chemical markers of the actinobacterial genera Salinospora and Marinophilus. pounds  have  no  antimicotic  activity,  typical  of  polyene antibiotics. Compounds (III) and (IV) are highly toxic to tumor  cells  at  concentrations  of  18.8  and  12.6  nM, respectively. Their activity against vancomycin(cid:2)resistant Enterococcus fascieum and methicillin(cid:2)resistant Staphy(cid:2) lococcus aureus is recorded at 0.125 and 0.625 μg/ml [16].

Two formerly unknown caprolactones were identi(cid:2) fied  in  a  lipid  extract  from  marine  Streptomyces  sp., isolate  B6007:  (6R,10S)(cid:2)methyl(cid:2)6(cid:2)dodecanolide  (V) and (R)(cid:2)10(cid:2)methyl(cid:2)6(cid:2)undecanolide (VI). This micro(cid:2) organism was detected in mangrove bottom sediments sampled near Papua New Guinea. The sequence of its 16S rRNA gene showed 99% similarity to the corre(cid:2) sponding Str. alborgriseolus gene. The structures of the compounds were derived from GLC and MS data and confirmed by synthesis. Compounds (V) and (VI) are MACROLIDES  AND  LACTONES  BY  MARINE  ACTINOBACTERIA Macrolides and lactones produced by marine actinobacteria. They inhibit the growth of Gram(cid:2)positive bacteria and possess anti(cid:2)Candida activity, but do not affect the growth of Gram(cid:2)negative bacteria [17]. New  butenolides  were  isolated  by  German  scien(cid:2) tists  from Streptomyces  sp.  strains  B5632  and  B3497. Compounds  (VII)–(IX)  suppress  Pseudomonas  aerugi(cid:2) nosa growth and inhibit chitinase activity in  Serratia marcescens [18].

Scientists of the Marine Natural Products Labora(cid:2) tory,  Korean  University,  Seoul,  found  three  more butenolides (MKN(cid:2)003A X), MKN(cid:2)003B (XII), and MKN(cid:2)003C (XIII)) and four 3(cid:2)hydroxy(cid:2)γ(cid:2)butyrolac(cid:2) tones  (MKN(cid:2)004a  (XI),  MKN(cid:2)004B  (XIV),  MKN(cid:2) 004C (XV), and MKN(cid:2)004D (XVI)) in a Streptomyces isolate [19].  The  total  extracts  where  compounds  (X)–(XVI) were detected displayed significant antifungal activity against  Candida  albicans,  but  neither  individual butenolides nor 3(cid:2)hydroxy(cid:2)γ(cid:2)butyrolactones had such activity. It  is  known  that  macrolide  antibiotics  are  highly active against Gram(cid:2)positive bacteria. Scientists of the Department of Organic Chemistry, University of Göt(cid:2) tingen, Germany, investigated Streptomyces sp. B7064 extracts  and  detected  already  known  chalcomycin  A (XVII) and a new macrolide, chalcomycin B (XVIII). These  compounds  are  active  against Bacillus subtilis, S.  aureus,  Escherichia  coli,  C.  albicans,  and  Mucor miehei [20]. In 2004, American scientists established the struc(cid:2) ture  of  aureoverticillactam  (XIX).  This  compound belongs to a new type of 22(cid:2)membered macrocycles. It is toxic to various tumor cell types. It was isolated from Str.  aureoverticillatus  NPS001583  sampled  from  sea bottom sediments [21].

A  formerly  unknown  macrolide,  micromono(cid:2) spolide  A  (XX),  was  found  by  Japanese  experts  in  a new actinobacterium of the genus Micromonospora. Its structure  and  relative  stereochemistry  were  deter(cid:2) mined by 2D NMR spectroscopy. Micromonospolide A inhibits starfish embryos at the gastrulation stage at IC50 = 10 mg/ml [22]. It is of special interest that a Streptomyces sp. strain sampled  from  bottom  sediments  near  the  Brazilian coast can cyclize γ(cid:2)hydroxyamino acids, including N(cid:2) acetyl(cid:2)γ(cid:2)hydroxyvaline, into lactones (XXI) [23]. Three  novel  macrolide  polyketides,  named  areni(cid:2) colides A–C ((XXII)–(XXIV)), were found in the act(cid:2) inobacterium Salinospora arenicola isolated from bot(cid:2) tom  sediments  at  a  30(cid:2)m  depth  near  the  island  of Guam,  United  States  [24].  These  compounds  are 26(cid:2)membered polyunsaturated macrolactones. The  analysis  of  biologically  active  compounds  in from  actinobacteria chloroform–ethanol  extracts  from the microbial collection of the University of Göt(cid:2) tingen  pointed  to  the  Streptomyces  sp.  strain  B6167. The bacterium had been found in North Sea water. It RUSSIAN  JOURNAL  OF  BIOORGANIC  CHEMISTRY   Vol.  36  BIOLOGICALLY  ACTIVE  METABOLITES  OF  MARINE  ACTINOBACTERIA

was shown to produce substances suppressing Gram(cid:2) positive  bacteria  [25].  Its  ethyl  acetate  extract  con(cid:2) tained three macrolide compounds, feigrisolides A, B, and C ((XXV)–(XXVII)). Their structural identity to macrolides formerly found in a soil isolate of Str. gri(cid:2) seus  [26]  was  confirmed  by  2D  NMR  spectroscopy and mass spectrometry. Feigrisolides are toxic to Ehr(cid:2) lich  carcinoma  cells  and  cells  of  the  sea  urchin Strongylocentrotus intermedius. Feigrisolide B (XXVI) inhibits the growth of Ehrlich carcinoma cells by 50% at IC50 = 3 μg/ml. It induces early apoptosis in these cells.  However,  this  compound  shows  no  antitumor activity in in vivo experiments. It also slows down the development  of  fertilized  sea  urchin  eggs  at  the  first division stage by 50% at IC50 = 1 μg/ml and entirely immobilizes sea urchin sperm at the same concentra(cid:2) tion.

Feigrisolide  A  (XXV)  displays  cytotoxic  activity against tumor cells and sea urchin embryos at higher concentrations than feigrisolide B (XXVI): IC50 = 20 and 30 μg/ml, respectively. Feigrisolide C is the least active of the three with regard to tumor cells and sea urchin  embryos:  IC50  =  50  μg/ml.  Feigrisolide  B inhibits Listeria monocytogenes 4(cid:2)B and S. aureus 3515 at 1 mg/ml, whereas the same feigrisolide C (XXVII) concentration accelerates E. coli growth. Feigrisolides A,  B,  and  C  at  a  concentration  of  1  mg/ml  have  no effect  on  the  growth  of  Proteus  vulgaris  4848, Pseudomonas aeruginosa H(cid:2)1515, Salmonella enteriti(cid:2) dis 126(cid:2)6, S. epidermidis 2482, or Yersinia pseudotuber(cid:2) culosis  H(cid:2)2781.  Feigrisolides  are  effectors  of  1  3(cid:2)β(cid:2)D(cid:2)glucanase  from  the  crystalline  style  of  Spisula sachalinensis. The enzyme activity is increased by 50% by feigrisolides B and C at the concentrations 0.4 and 0.2 mM, respectively, whereas feigrisolide A inhibits it by 50% at 0.4 mM.

Neomarinone  (XXVIII),  a  cytotoxic  naphtho(cid:2) quinone derivative, was found in an unidentified acti(cid:2) nobacterium investigated by researchers of Prof. Fen(cid:2) ical’s laboratory [27]. The bacterium had been isolated from bottom sediments of the Batiquitos Lagoon near San  Diego,  United  States.  Two(cid:2)dimensional  NMR studies proved the Z geometry of the double bond in the side chain and the E orientation of methyl groups in the dihydrofuran cycle. The  cytotoxic  quinocyclin  antibiotic  kosinostatin (XXIX) was isolated from the culture liquid of the act(cid:2) inobacterium Microminospora sp. TPA(cid:2)0468 obtained from water of Toyama Bay, Japan [28, 29]. The antibi(cid:2) otic  inhibits  Gram(cid:2)negative  bacteria  at  the  minimal inhibiting concentration MIC = 0.039 μg/ml. Gram(cid:2) negative  bacteria  and  yeast  are  inhibited  at  MIC  = 1.56–12.5  μg/ml.  Kosinostatin  is  toxic  to  various tumor  cell  types.  It  inhibits  human  DNA  topo(cid:2) QUINOID  BIOLOGICALLY  ACTIVE  SUBSTANCES  FROM  MARINE  ACTINOBACTERIA RUSSIAN  JOURNAL  OF  BIOORGANIC  CHEMISTRY   Vol.  36  SOBOLEVSKAYA,  KUZNETSOVA RUSSIAN  JOURNAL  OF  BIOORGANIC  CHEMISTRY   Vol.  36  BIOLOGICALLY  ACTIVE  METABOLITES  OF  MARINE  ACTINOBACTERIA (XLVII) R = H; (XLVIII) R = Cl Quinoid biologically active compounds from marine actinobacteria. isomerase  IIα.  Kosinostatin  is  an  isomer  of  iso(cid:2) quinocyclin  B  (XXX),  formerly  isolated  from  a  soil Str. aureofaciens strain.

New  anthracycline  antibiotics  himalomycins  A (XXXI) and B (XXXII) were obtained from Streptomy(cid:2) ces  sp.  B6921,  formerly  found  in  bottom  sediments near the island of Mauritius. They inhibit Gram(cid:2)posi(cid:2) tive and Gram(cid:2)negative bacteria [30]. is  a metabolite of Actinomadura sp. BL(cid:2)42(cid:2)P013(cid:2)046 iso(cid:2) lated from bottom sediments near the northern coast of  Spain.  Its  structure  was  determined  by  2D  NMR spectroscopy. It suppresses tumors and inhibits Gram(cid:2) positive bacteria [31, 32]. Lomaiviticins  A  (XXXIV)  and  B  (XXXV)  are  new antibiotics isolated from Micromonospora lomaivitien(cid:2) sis associated with the marine ascidian Polysyncraton lithostrotum. The unusual dimeric glycosylated diazo(cid:2) benzofluorene  structure  of  these  metabolites  was proven by high(cid:2)resolution mass spectrometry and 2D NMR  spectroscopy.  Lomaiviticins  contain  an N,N(cid:2)dimethylated  derivative  of  pyrrolosamine,  a monosaccharide  seldom  occurring  in  natural  com(cid:2) pounds.  Lomaiviticins  are  potent  DNA(cid:2)damaging agents. Lomaiviticin A showed cytotoxic activity com(cid:2) parable with that of the antitumor agents mitomycin C and adriamycin in tests with 24 tumor cell lines [33].

Initially, Japanese and American scientists headed the study of marine actinobacterial metabolites. Later, they  were  joined  by  many  research  teams  in  Europe and  Southeast  Asia.  Researchers  of  the  Institute  of Molecular and Cell Biology, Singapore, isolated strep(cid:2) 7(cid:2)(1(cid:2)methyl(cid:2)2(cid:2)oxopro(cid:2) tonigrin  pyl)streptonigrin (XXXVII) from Micromonospora sp. IM2670. These compounds induce apoptosis in cells of human neuroblastoma SH(cid:2)SY5Y [34]. Streptomyces sp. KS3, isolated from bottom sediments near Komodo Island (Indonesia), produces anthracy(cid:2) cline  antibiotics:  komodoquinones  A  (XXXVIII)  and B (XXXIX). The former induces the differentiation of neuroblastoma cells [35, 36]. German and Chinese scientists in cooperation iso(cid:2) lated  antibiotics  named  chinikomycins  A  (XLI)  and B (XLII). They are chlorinated derivatives of the com(cid:2) monly known antibiotic manumycin A (XL) isolated by German scientists from Str. parvulus in 1963. Chin(cid:2) ikomycins possess slight antitumor activity [37]. Three new chlorinated dihydroquinones, (XLIII), (XLIV), and (XLV), were isolated from the CNQ(cid:2)525 marine  actinobacterium  strain.  It  had  been  obtained from bottom sediments sampled at a 152(cid:2)m depth near La  Jola  Island,  California.  These  compounds  are potent  antibiotics.  They  inhibit  human  carcinoma HCT(cid:2)116 cells [38].

The marine streptomycete Streptomyces sp. associ(cid:2) ated with the glasswort Salicornia herbacea (Qingdao, China) was found to produce hitherto unknown 1,9(cid:2) (XLVI) dihydroxy(cid:2)2(cid:2)ethyl(cid:2)3(cid:2)methylanthraquinone  along with known compounds: octadecanoic acid and Cytotoxic  xanthone  IB(cid:2)00208  (XXXIII)  RUSSIAN  JOURNAL  OF  BIOORGANIC  CHEMISTRY   Vol.  36  SOBOLEVSKAYA,  KUZNETSOVA inhibits cholest(cid:2)4(cid:2)en(cid:2)3(cid:2)one.  Compound  tumor cells HL(cid:2)60, BCTC(cid:2)823 MDA, and MB(cid:2)435 at 6.83, 82.2, and 56.59 μg/ml, respectively [39]. Two cytotoxic quinones, marmycins A (XLVII) and B  (XLVIII),  were  obtained  by  American  scientists from  a  marine  streptomycete  found  in  bottom  sedi(cid:2) ments  in  the  Sea  of  Cortez,  Mexico.  The  antitumor activity of marmycin A with regard to human HCT(cid:2) 116 cells is 18 times greater than that of its chlorinated derivative  (XLVIII).  This  observation  is  surprising, because the introduction of chlorine generally increases the pharmacological activity of compounds [40].

Biologically  active  compounds  were  detected  in chloroform–ethanol  extracts  of  facultative  marine actinobacteria isolated from sea objects by researchers of the Laboratory of Microbial Metabolite Chemistry, Pacific  Institute  of  Bioorganic  Chemistry,  Vladivos(cid:2) tok, Russia, during an expedition of the research vessel Akademik Oparin [41]. A strain identified by morpho(cid:2) logical and biochemical features as Nocardia sp. pro(cid:2) duced  cytotoxic  compounds,  which  inhibited  the development of fertilized S. intermedius eggs at MIC = 40 μg/ml and induced the lysis of murine erythrocytes at MIC = 30–50 μg/ml. Chromatography of the acti(cid:2) nobacterium extract on silica gel with gradient mobile phases of increasing polarity and reverse(cid:2)phase HPLC yielded  compound  (XLIX),  which  constituted  7%  of the  total  chloroform–ethanolic  extract.  Mass  spec(cid:2) trometry  and  NMR  data  indicated  that  (XLIX)  was ubiquinone Q9 [41]. 1,4(cid:2)Benzoquinones are widespread in nature. They are  found  mainly  in  fungi  and  various  higher  plants [42]. They also occur in marine bacteria of the genera Alteromonas,  Marinomonas,  Deleya,  Shewanella,  and Pseudomonas.  Bacteria  of  the  genera  Pseudomonas and  Marinomonas  contain  mainly  ubiquinone  Q8. Ubiquinone  Q9  has  been  found  in  Deleya  and the  genus Pseudomonas,  whereas  bacteria  of  Shewanella  produce  mixtures  of  ubiquinones, menaquinones,  and  methylmenaquinones  [42,  43]. Actinobacteria  were  the  first  source  from  which ubiquinone with nine isoprenyl residues was isolated.

A  new  cyclic  dipeptide  (L)  was  isolated  from Micromonospora sp. It inhibits the growth of Saccha(cid:2) romyces cerevisiae at MIC = 32 μg/ml, but shows no activity against S. aureus, E. coli, or C. albicans [44]. Two  peptides,  (LI)  and  (LII),  belonging  to  the nocardamine  class  of  antibiotics  were  obtained  from the culture liquid of a Streptomyces isolate associated with an unidentified marine sponge [45]. Three depsipeptides were isolated from Streptomy(cid:2) ces  sp.  found  in  marine  deposits  near  Guam  Island, United  States.  They  are  piperazimycins  A  (LIII),  B (LIV), and C (LV). These hexadepsipeptides contain rare  acids:  hydroxyacetic,  γ(cid:2)hydroxypiperazinic,  and DIKETOPIPERAZINES  AND  CYCLIC  PEPTIDES

γ(cid:2)chloropiperazinic.  Piperazimycins  A  and  C  were also  found  to  contain  previously  unknown  amino and acids:  2(cid:2)amino(cid:2)8(cid:2)methyldeca(cid:2)4,6(cid:2)dienoic,  respectively. The  biologic  activity  of  compounds  (LIII)–(LV) against human carcinoma HCT(cid:2)116 cells was studied in  vitro.  Piperazimycins  displayed  a  significant  cyto(cid:2) toxic effect against these cells at IC50 = 76 ng/ml [46]. Two  new  diketopiperazines,  cyclomarazines  A (LVI) and B (LVII), and the cyclic heptapeptide cyclo(cid:2) marine D (LVIII) were isolated from the marine acti(cid:2) nobacterium  S.  arenicola  [47].  This  organism  was found  in  marine  deposits  sampled  at  a  20(cid:2)m  depth near  Palau  Islands,  Philippine  Sea.  The  compounds include rare amino acids: N(cid:2)(1,1(cid:2)dimethylallyl)tryp(cid:2) tophan  and  δ(cid:2)hydroxyleucine.  Cyclomarines  are RUSSIAN  JOURNAL  OF  BIOORGANIC  CHEMISTRY   Vol.  36  2(cid:2)amino(cid:2)8(cid:2)methylnona(cid:2)4,6(cid:2)dienoic  BIOLOGICALLY  ACTIVE  METABOLITES  OF  MARINE  ACTINOBACTERIA Diketopiperazines and cyclic peptides. (LIII) R1 = OH, R2 = CH3; (LIV) R1 = H, R2 = CH3; (LV) R1 = OH, R2 = CH2CH3 known as antitumor agents. They were first described as metabolites of the terrestrial streptomycete Strepto(cid:2) myces sp. CNB(cid:2)982 [48].

We found that Streptomyces sp. KMM 7210 isolated from the bottom sediments of Trinity Bay (Possiet Bay, Japan Sea) produced compounds suppressing the growth of Gram(cid:2)positive bacteria and toxic to embryos of the sea urchin S. intermedius [49]. A novel compound, dipeptide cyclo(glycil(cid:2)L(cid:2)tyrosyl (LIX), was isolated from the active fraction. Its cytotoxic activity was judged from the dam(cid:2) age of S. intermedius sperm cells and eggs. Membranes of sperm cells were damaged at 50 μg/ml by 25%, whereas egg membranes remained intact. However, the growing sea urchin embryos were more susceptible to (LIX). The compound  arrested  embryo  division  at  the  stage  of  2– 4 blastomeres. (LVI) R = CH3; (LVII) R = H ALKALOIDS  OF  MARINE  ACTINOBACTERIA Several new phenazine antibiotics were isolated by German scientists from Str. anulatus associated with a bivalve: endophenazines A (LX), B (LXI), C (LXII), and D (LXIII). They possess fungicidal and herbicidal activities and suppress Gram(cid:2)positive bacteria [50]. In 2004, American scientists isolated a new diben(cid:2) zodiazepine  alkaloid,  diazepinomycin  (LXIV),  from Micromonospora  sp.  DPJ12  [51].  The  dibenzodiaz(cid:2) epine  moiety  present  in  this  compound  is  extremely rare in nature.

The  marine  isolate  Streptomyces  sp.  NPS  00818 found  in  bottom  sediments  near  Alaska  produces  a series  of  pyrrole  sesquiterpenes:  glaciapyrroles  A (LXV),  B  (LXVI),  and  C  (LXVII).  Glaciapyrrole  A inhibits  adenocarcinoma  HT(cid:2)29  and  melanoma B16(cid:2)F10 cells. Glaciapyrroles B and C show no such activity [52]. amorphane  sesquiterpenes  In  2007,  Prof.  Laatsch  et  al.  discovered  three in  Streptomyces  sp. SOBOLEVSKAYA,  KUZNETSOVA Azameron  (LXVIII)  is  a  new  meroterpenoid  iso(cid:2) lated from marine streptomycete Streptomyces sp. Its structure  includes  a  chloropyranophthalazinone  core and  a  3(cid:2)chloro(cid:2)6(cid:2)hydroxy(cid:2)2,2,6(cid:2)trimethylcyclohexyl(cid:2) methyl group as a side chain [53]. Azameron is the first natural  compound  possessing  a  unique  phthalazine cyclic  system.  It  displays  weak  cytotoxic  activity against murine splenocytes, T cells, and macrophages at IC50 = 40 μM. Synthetic compounds with phthala(cid:2) zine(cid:2)5,8(cid:2)quinone  cores  inhibit  topoisomerase,  and the cytotoxic activity of azameron may also be related to topoisomerase inhibition.

Streptocordin  (LXIX),  a  cytotoxic  compound belonging to methylpyridines, was isolated by Korean scientists from Streptomyces sp. found in marine sedi(cid:2) ments of Ayu Island, Pacific Ocean [54]. It has antitu(cid:2) mor and antibacterial activities. M491  sampled  near  the  Qingdao  coast,  China: 10α,11(cid:2)dihydroxyamorph(cid:2)4(cid:2)ene  (LXX),  10α,15(cid:2)dihy(cid:2) droxyamorph(cid:2)4(cid:2)ene(cid:2)3(cid:2)one (LXXI), and 5α,10α,11(cid:2)tri(cid:2) hydroxyamorph(cid:2)3(cid:2)one  (LXXII)  [55].  They  inhibit RUSSIAN  JOURNAL  OF  BIOORGANIC  CHEMISTRY   Vol.  36  BIOLOGICALLY  ACTIVE  METABOLITES  OF  MARINE  ACTINOBACTERIA (LXXXII) R = H; (LXXXIII) R = CH3 (LXXXIV) R1 = CH3, R2 = (LXXXV) R1 = CH3, R2 =  Other bioactive compounds from marine actinomycetes. Lajollamycin, an antibiotic of the spiro(cid:2)β(cid:2)lactone(cid:2) γ(cid:2)lactam  structure  (LXXIII),  was  isolated  from Str. nodosus  NPS007994.  The  microorganism  was found in bottom sediments near California. The anti(cid:2) biotic  inhibits  Gram(cid:2)positive  bacteria  and  B16(cid:2)F10 tumor cells [56]. Lorneamides A (LXXIV) and B (LXXV) were found in a marine actinomycete, isolate MST(cid:2)MA190 [57]. It was found in coastal sand sampled on the southwest(cid:2) ern coast of Australia. These substances are amides of acids  with  ω(cid:2)aryl  moieties.  Lorneamide  A  is  active against B. subtilis, but lorneamide B is not. Indole nucleosides kahakamides A (LXXVI) and B (LXXVII)  were  isolated  from  the  actinobacterium Nocardiopsis  dassonvillei  found  in  bottom  sediments near Kauai island, Hawaii. These compounds belong to the neosidomycin antibiotic series. Kahakamide A inhibits Gram(cid:2)positive bacteria. The biologic activity of kahakamide B has not yet been studied [58]. Disubstituted indole (LXXVIII) was isolated from the mycelium of the marine streptomycete Streptomy(cid:2) ces  sp.  LB(cid:2)49(cid:2)58(cid:2)005.  The  compound  was  tested  on 14 tumor cell lines. It was found to be active against some leukemia types [59].

Metabolites  of  the  actinobacterium  Str.  platensis isolated  from  the  water  of  Toyama  Bay,  Japan, included  antibiotics  of  a  new  structural  type:  lydica(cid:2) mycin (LXXIX), TPU(cid:2)0037(cid:2)A (LXXX), TPU(cid:2)0037(cid:2)B (LXXXI), TPU(cid:2)0037(cid:2)C (LXXXII), and TPU(cid:2)0037(cid:2)D (LXXXIII). They inhibit a methicillin(cid:2)resistant strain of S. aureus, IC50 = 1.56–12.6 μg/ml [60]. thiazostatin  analogs,  watasemycins  A (LXXXIV) and B (LXXXV), were isolated from another marine  streptomycete  found  in  Toyama  Bay  water. These  compounds  have  wide  ranges  of  antibiotic activity  against  Gram(cid:2)positive  and  Gram(cid:2)negative bacteria and yeast [61]. The ethyl acetate extract of Streptomyces sp. B8652 is highly active against St. aureus, E. coli, and B. subti(cid:2) lis.  The  activity  is  associated  with  parimycin (LXXXVI). Other activities of this compound are fun(cid:2) gicidal and microalgae suppression [62]. At the con(cid:2) centration  IC50  =  0.9–6.7  μg/ml,  it  inhibits  human tumor  cells:  stomach  cancer  (line  GXF25IL),  breast cancer (MSF(cid:2)7 and MAXF 401NL), and melanoma (MFXF 462NL and MEXF 514L).

The  study  of  polar  Streptomyces  species  revealed the structure of gutingimycin (LXXXVII). This com(cid:2) pound  belongs  to  trioxacarcin  antibiotics.  It  inhibits Gram(cid:2)positive and Gram(cid:2)negative bacteria [63]. New antibiotics chandrananimycins A (LXXXVIII), B (LXXXIX), and C (XC) were isolated from the culture liquid  of  Actinomadura  sp.  M045,  which  had  been found  in  bottom  sediments  of  Jiaozhou  Bay,  China. These compounds are active against various tumor cell RUSSIAN  JOURNAL  OF  BIOORGANIC  CHEMISTRY   Vol.  36  BIOLOGICALLY  ACTIVE  METABOLITES  OF  MARINE  ACTINOBACTERIA types: melanoma, breast cancer, and lung carcinoma; IC70 = 1.4 μg/ml [64]. Two new polyketides, actinofuranones A (XCI) and B (XCII), were obtained from marine Streptomyces sp. CNQ766. Their biologic activity is unknown [65]. Four new compounds were isolated from the cul(cid:2) ture liquid of Streptomyces sp. CNQ(cid:2)185 [66]. Three of them  were  named  daryamides  A  (XCIII),  B  (XCIV), and C (XCV). The fourth was the amide of (2E,4E)(cid:2)7(cid:2) methylocta(cid:2)2,4(cid:2)dienoic  acid  (XCVI).  Compound (XCIII)  is  toxic  to  human  tumor  cells  at  IC50  = 3.15 μg/ml.  The  daryamides  have  no  antibacterial activity.

Two new compounds of the piericidin series, pieri(cid:2) cidins  C7  (XCVII)  and  C8  (XCVIII),  were  isolated from marine Streptomyces sp. associated with an uni(cid:2) dentified  ascidian  sampled  in  Iwayama  Bay,  Palau Island, at a 0.5(cid:2)m depth [67]. Piericidins display sig(cid:2) nificant inhibitory action in rat glial cells and murine neuroblastoma cells. The  data  reviewed  herein  illustrate  the  broad chemical  diversity  of  metabolites  of  marine  obligate and facultative actinobacteria. Further studies of these metabolites  will  provide  new  biologically  active  sub(cid:2) stances for bioorganic chemists and allow their poten(cid:2) tial  in  medicine,  agriculture,  and  mariculture  of marine invertebrates and algae to be assessed.
